---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const layerOrderExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;

const legacyImportExample = `@import './legacy/site.css' layer(legacy);
@import './components/product-card.css' layer(components);`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS Migration"
    description="Migrating existing projects toward Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">Migration</p>

        <h1>
            Migrating existing CSS
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            LSCSS is designed for gradual adoption. You should not need to stop
            work, rewrite the whole frontend, or pretend legacy CSS never
            happened.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Migration principles
        </h2>

        <div class="hub-card-grid">
            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Contain first
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Put existing CSS in a known place before changing how new
                    CSS is written.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Improve new work
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Apply LSCSS to new components first. Do not pause delivery
                    while chasing perfect old code.
                </p>
            </article>

            <article class="hub-card">
                <h3>
                    Delete over time
                </h3>

                <p>
                    Migration is successful when legacy CSS gets smaller, not
                    when it gets renamed.
                </p>
            </article>
        </div>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Recommended migration path
        </h2>

        <ol>
            <li>Introduce the layer order.</li>
            <li>Move old CSS into the legacy layer.</li>
            <li>Put design tokens and settings in the settings layer.</li>
            <li>Move broad element defaults into the base layer.</li>
            <li>Write new components as small component partials.</li>
            <li>Reduce selector depth when touching existing components.</li>
            <li>Replace unclear names with semantic component names.</li>
            <li>Use modifiers for real variants and state classes for temporary states.</li>
            <li>Move emergency fixes into the hacks layer with comments.</li>
            <li>Delete old CSS when the related UI is replaced or refactored.</li>
        </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Step 1: define the cascade order
        </h2>

        <p>
            Add the layer order before moving code. This gives the project a
            stable override model from the start.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={layerOrderExample} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Step 2: isolate legacy CSS
        </h2>

        <p>
            Existing CSS can temporarily live inside the legacy layer while new
            work follows the modern structure.
        </p>

        <CodeExample code={legacyImportExample} />
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What not to do
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Do not rename every class without changing the architecture.</li>
            <li>Do not move all legacy code into components and call it migrated.</li>
            <li>Do not create a hacks layer and leave everything there forever.</li>
            <li>Do not add specificity to beat legacy CSS when layer order can solve it.</li>
            <li>Do not block feature work for a full rewrite unless the project genuinely needs one.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Definition of done
        </h2>

        <p>
            A migration is working when new CSS follows the system, old CSS is
            contained, overrides are predictable, and the legacy layer keeps
            getting smaller.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
